text.tspan: Wealth Manager
Recent Commentary
ABN AMRO
ABN AMRO announced the acquisition of Hauck Aufhäuser Lampe (HAL) in May 2024 to strengthen its top-3 position in the
German wealth market, and is open to bolt-on opportunities in Wealth Management - we expect to hear more from the new CEO
Berard at the CMD in November.
BNP Paribas
BNP Paribas acquired Axa-IM in July, creating one of Europe’s largest asset managers with €1.5T AUM. In Wealth Management,
BNP has announced the acquisition of HSBC's German Private banking. The bank is focused on developing a large and integrated
platform across its insurance, asset management, and wealth management businesses.
CaixaBank
CaixaBank’s CEO stated the bank is not considering any M&A transactions as part of its strategic plan, focusing instead on
organic growth and digital transformation.
Crédit Agricole
Crédit Agricole’s Indosuez Wealth Management acquired a majority stake in Degroof Petercam in 2024 and recently bought
Banque Thaler in Switzerland, and BNP's clients in Monaco. In July 2025, Credit Agricole announced the purchase of French
private bank and wealth manager Milleis Group through its LCL and Crédit Agricole Assurances subsidiaries. CASA has a track
record at successfully deploying excess capital towards bolt-on acquisitions: we expect to hear more at the upcoming CMD in
November.
Deutsche Bank
Deutsche Bank overall is currently focused on self-help, and improving profitability on a stand-alone basis rather than via M&A.
Within Wealth Management business however the bank wants to grow, and has been investing in hiring relationship managers.
Intesa Sanpaolo
Intesa is avoiding large M&A deals, citing antitrust limits and high valuations. CEO Carlo Messina prefers organic growth and
talent acquisition, for example hiring 151 private bankers in Q1 2025, bringing in 1.5bn of AUM. Intesa is working with BlackRock
to create a new Digital Wealth Management platform targeting European Private and Affluent clients, beginning with Belgium and
Luxembourg, and this partnership aims to accelerate the growth of digital wealth management offerings across Europe
Julius Baer
Julius Baer has been streamlining its portfolio, and for example it sold its Brazilian operations to BTG Pactual and Kairos in Italy.
New leadership however has stated that the bank wants to show organic growth and a successful turnaround before engaging in
M&A.
Natwest
Natwest has indicated that high multiples in the wealth management sector make it challenging for the bank to pursue growth
through takeovers. Despite these challenges, the bank has acknowledged the appeal of a larger wealth business with its capital-
light income and demographic advantages
UBS
After acquiring Credit Suisse in 2023, UBS has been focused on integration across Asia, EMEA and Switzerland, which is planned
to be completed by year end 2026. In the US, UBS is for now focused on closing the profitability gap vs peers, but Chairman
Kelleher has stated (for example in NZZ interview March 2024) that the bank may consider acquisitions to expand channels and
scale, although this may be challenged by the recent capital proposal in Switzerland.
